<assessment id="u4_m1_confintprop3_digt_tutor3">
    <title>Tutor</title>
    <question id="q1">
        <body>Recall that <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T103628-0500"?>when
            <?oxy_insert_end?>using a 95% confidence level, to achieve a 2% margin of error, we must
            have a minimum sample size of
            2<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T103634-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>500.
            If we are willing to increase the desired margin of error (to be larger than 2%), the
            sample size that we need will:</body>
        <multiple_choice shuffle="false">
            <choice value="A">decrease</choice>
            <choice value="B">increase</choice>
            <choice value="C">not be affected</choice>
        </multiple_choice>
        <part>
            <response match="A" score="10">
                <feedback>Correct. The intuitive explanation is that if we are willing to accept a
                    larger error, we can sample fewer subjects. Conversely, to be more precise, we
                    must sample more subjects.</feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="B">
                <feedback>Incorrect. If we are willing to accept a larger error, would
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T103713-0500"?>we<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T103712-0500" content="you"?>
                    sample fewer or more subjects? Please try again.</feedback>
            </response>
            <response match="C">
                <feedback>Incorrect. If we are willing to accept a larger error, would
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T103716-0500"?>we<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101126T103715-0500" content="you"?>
                    sample fewer or more subjects? Please try again.</feedback>
            </response>
        </part>
    </question>
</assessment>
